WEBVTT

00:00:00.031 --> 00:00:02.617
In Vienna, two maternity wards sat under

00:00:02.617 --> 00:00:05.376
one hospital roof. The First Clinic was

00:00:05.376 --> 00:00:06.700
run by doctors and students.

00:00:07.602 --> 00:00:09.144
The Second was run by midwives.

00:00:09.926 --> 00:00:11.087
The patients were similar.

00:00:11.868 --> 00:00:13.111
The death rates were not.

00:00:14.071 --> 00:00:17.185
By 1846, the First Clinic was losing

00:00:17.185 --> 00:00:19.440
more than one in ten mothers.

00:00:19.440 --> 00:00:22.436
Across the same years, the Second stayed

00:00:22.436 --> 00:00:24.810
under four percent. Semmelweis found the

00:00:24.810 --> 00:00:25.989
difference in the routine.

00:00:26.048 --> 00:00:29.435
Doctors moved from autopsies to childbirth

00:00:29.435 --> 00:00:32.950
without effective disinfection. He

00:00:32.950 --> 00:00:34.655
required chloride-of-lime hand

00:00:34.655 --> 00:00:39.121
disinfection. Mortality fell. The evidence

00:00:39.121 --> 00:00:41.206
worked before germ theory could explain

00:00:41.206 --> 00:00:43.774
why. That was the problem.

00:00:43.774 --> 00:00:46.020
Believing the data meant believing doctors

00:00:46.020 --> 00:00:47.920
had been carrying death from the dead

00:00:47.920 --> 00:00:50.244
to the living. The institution protected

00:00:50.244 --> 00:00:52.693
its identity longer than it protected the

00:00:52.693 --> 00:00:56.066
evidence. Small causes, massive

00:00:56.066 --> 00:00:57.392
consequences.
